<div id="review_22598384" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/22598384" />
    <a title="Diane Ramirez" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/226426-diane-ramirez"><img alt="Diane Ramirez" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/22598384?book_show_action=true">May 19, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Diane Ramirez" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Diane Ramirez" href="/user/show/226426-diane-ramirez">Diane Ramirez</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer22598384" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2340398451570025374">This book was nothing short of a revelation for me. James Baldwin writes beautiful, powerful, conflicted, and brutal portrayals of life as an African American in the mid 20th century. Some of his essays -- the analyses of books and movies that touch on black life in the US, for example -- suffered a bit in their age. But the personal stuff? How where he grew up, in Harlem, like in other urban pockets of black-populated ghettos, the fathers hide their anger, their having to make compromises, in o</span>
  <span id="freeText2340398451570025374" style="display:none">This book was nothing short of a revelation for me. James Baldwin writes beautiful, powerful, conflicted, and brutal portrayals of life as an African American in the mid 20th century. Some of his essays -- the analyses of books and movies that touch on black life in the US, for example -- suffered a bit in their age. But the personal stuff? How where he grew up, in Harlem, like in other urban pockets of black-populated ghettos, the fathers hide their anger, their having to make compromises, in order to raise their children to be strong? How demeaning it is to be refused service at an airport cocktail lounge, with a room full of white, silent onlookers? How he can't fathom where children got the courage to walk through crowds of angry white mobs in order to get educated in schools where they weren't wanted? Or how their mothers got the strength to send their babies through that? I've never read anything like this. His pain and anger and his plea for this country (and this world) to move beyond color barriers into the beautiful and complex creatures we are as humans -- it's an important work that I'm now recommending to everybody I encounter.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2340398451570025374" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

