    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_50877129" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/50877129" />
    <a title="Lloyd Scott" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2169014-lloyd-scott"><img alt="Lloyd Scott" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442476692p2/2169014.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/50877129?book_show_action=true">Mar 29, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lloyd Scott" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lloyd Scott" href="/user/show/2169014-lloyd-scott">Lloyd Scott</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer50877129" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6021056527369534295"><br/>The amazing james baldwin.<br/><br/>For me as an educated black man this was a difficult read yet an honest and a profound read. This collection of mr. baldwin&apos;s essays go way back to his childhood and beyond, and especially the horrors that he dealt with growing up as a young black kid in harlem, and being harrassed by white cops who took him into the alley to see how big his private part was.<br/><br/>As usual mr. baldwin&apos;s voice resonates with honest, frank words that he writes ever so eloquently yet truthful. Y</span>
  <span id="freeText6021056527369534295" style="display:none"><br />The amazing james baldwin.<br /><br />For me as an educated black man this was a difficult read yet an honest and a profound read. This collection of mr. baldwin's essays go way back to his childhood and beyond, and especially the horrors that he dealt with growing up as a young black kid in harlem, and being harrassed by white cops who took him into the alley to see how big his private part was.<br /><br />As usual mr. baldwin's voice resonates with honest, frank words that he writes ever so eloquently yet truthful. You get a chance to be inside of the mind of one of the greatest literary voices of the 20th century, and it is quite a mind and quite a voice to explore, to see, to visit and to learn from. This is quite a read, powerful at times, in fact it is powerful many times over; it has been hard for me to read the entire book and I have had it since 1988. I still have the book, it amasses easily over 700pp, I have never gotten through half of it but I will finish it someday. His words are powerful, frank, to the point, hard to take sometime but they are true and honest.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6021056527369534295" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


